“If humans had not coexisted before, we would not have been able to reach this far”, says Sanjeev Pednekar, Founder of PRANI when asked about coexistence. 🤝🏻

In a country as ecologically diverse as India, we have always found ways to share spaces with different species that coexist alongside us. With rapid urbanisation, habitat loss due to climate change, and a disconnect between humans and natural landscapes, our tolerance towards fellow species that we share the planet with, has reduced. 🐍🐘🌿

“Sharing Cities: Coexistence in the Urbanscape” is a collaborative awareness and outreach initiative between Rainmatter and organisations working in the conservation and coexistence space. The aim is to be able to better understand the incredible biodiversity that surrounds us and is critical to an urban landscape, as well as to navigate coexistence with the many species we share it with. 🏙️🌱

We would love to hear some of the most fascinating stories of human-wildlife coexistence that you have heard or have experienced. Drop them in the comments. 💬

#shareyourspaces #coexistence #urban #awareness #education

In a country like India, humans and wildlife have always shared spaces, finding ways to coexist. With a fast urbanising society, habitat loss due to climate change, and a disconnect between humans and natural landscapes, these interactions sometimes turn sour, leading to tension and losses for all. 🐅🐘

“Sharing Cities: Coexistence in the Urbanscape” is an ongoing collaborative awareness and outreach initiative between Rainmatter and organisations working in the conservation and coexistence space. The aim is to be able to better understand the incredible biodiversity that surrounds us and is critical to an urban landscape, as well as to navigate coexistence with the many species we share it with. 🏙️🌿

An animal group often misunderstood in this context, and deeply feared, is snakes. In a conversation between Gerry (The Liana Trust), Sumanth (HSI-India), Sandeep (The Good Earth - Malhar) and Tanmayi (Rainmatter Foundation), they talk about the cruciality of snakes and other overlooked animals in an urban ecosystem, the changing relationship between humans and their environment, how it might be time for us to rethink our long-held perceptions, and how positive conversations can be the beginning of lasting change. 🐍

Check out the full episode now on Youtube, link in bio. 🔗🐍🐘

#shareyourspace #coexistence #snakes #urban #conservation

“Snakes will remember to avenge the death of its partner.” 
“Snakes don’t belong in an urban vicinity.” 
“Snakes can take the form of a woman, and vice versa”... 

How many of these myths and misconceptions have we grown up listening to? 🐍

While some might sound outrageous at the outset, long-held beliefs perpetuated through stories and media, tend to form lasting, inaccurate perceptions about a number of wonderful species crucial to the well-being of our environment. 🎥 

 
At the beautiful Liana Trust, that has been conducting significant research and outreach work related to snakes and human-animal coexistence, Gerry (The Liana Trust), Sumanth (HSI-India), Sandeep (The GoodEarth - Malhar) and Tanmayi (Rainmatter Foundation) delve deeper into the idea of what it really means to “Share our Cities”. 🔍

 

Full video COMING SOON on Rainmatter’s YouTube channel! 
Stay tuned, link to Youtube channel in bio.🔗

#shareyourspace #coexistence #snakes #podcast #urbancoexistence

Whenever we see a snake in our surroundings, our first response is to try and remove them. We either try to do it ourselves, or try to call someone who can help us in relocating the snake.

Gerry Martin, Herpetologist & Founder Trustee of The Liana Trust helped us in breaking the misconceptions surrounding snake rescue and relocation. 🐍

MISCONCEPTION:
We should rescue and relocate a snake whenever we see one in our vicinity.

FACT:
Contrary to popular belief, snakes, like other birds, insects or reptiles we see commonly in our localities, are often not misplaced or wandering individuals, but belong to the area they are found in. They have a crucial role to play in the urban ecosystem by helping keep in check the rodent and other pest populations. In the absence of snakes, these pests would multiply, leading to a chain reaction of more snakes being attracted to the area due to the easy availability of prey.⚖️

Most of the commonly found snakes are harmless and the panic that we often experience is mostly because we tend to bucket all snakes as harmful, leading to a heightened sense of perceived danger. Knowing how to identify the commonly found snake species around us is the first step that we can take to peacefully coexist with them. An intervention by expert snake handlers is only necessary when you spot a medically significant snake indoors.

Like Gerry mentions, we also have to be extremely aware that we are removing the snake from the “situation” and not from the “location” to a faraway habitat not native to theirs - which often leads to the death of the relocated snake. ⚠️

Let us know in the comments about your experiences whenever you have come across a snake in your area. 💬

Note - Medically significant snakes are the ones who have been known to cause human mortality or morbidity in case there’s an unfortunate interaction.

#shareyourspace #coexistence #snake #knowledge #expert

There's so much happening all the time around us and blending in to all that allows us to witness dynamics in Nature. No less amazing than the well known alarm calls of deer and langur to the presence of a big cat is the unmistakable call made by palm squirrels when they spot a rat snake, Russell's viper or cobra. 
Watching these extremely skittish animals, both the squirrels and the rat snake, takes some patience and stillness. Moments like these are unparalleled in my mind. #backyardbiodiversity #snakesofinstagram #ecology

For a bunch of us who have had the good fortune  of herping alongside Rom Whitaker, India's original Snake Man and iconic herpetologist, the sight of a Whitaker's boa ( Eryx whitakeri) always brings a smile. 
Bah..why not a more handsome looking dude of a snake that's named after me he said, as he lifted this specimen up in Goa a few years ago. 
Here, we have seen the Golden iris beauties on beaches and plateaus, in coconut palms and shoes, and of course mistaken as baby pythons a zillion times over.
Non venomous and quiet in nature ( susegad if I may say so), these are efficient rodent controllers and the best snakes to have in the neighborhood or garden. 
Endemic to South India and amazing to observe this is amongst Goa's common snakes and is also a victim of road kills due to its slow movement.
@assavri_kulkarni and me have shared a home garden with one individual for over 9 years so much so that guests knew of its existence and favorite spot near the coconut palm.

Understanding the Psychological Impacts of Snakebite

This Sunday was quite an overwhelming experience. We invited snakebite survivors from across the Hunsur Taluk to participate in focus group discussions led by a team from the Clinical Psychology Society of India to understand and document the psychological impact of snakebite. 

Survivors alluded to being ostracised by neighbours, friends and even family in some cases. Some hadn’t spoken of it for years and said they felt like a weight had been lifted as they’d bottled it all in so far, never being able to voice their feelings or allow their sense of trauma to show. Further, many have permanent damage and experience a diminishing of self worth, and compromised quality of life and ability to earn. 

This is the first of many engagements with the community that we will be conducting in collaboration with Humane Society International/ India. We seek to better understand the reality of snakebite in rural agrarian communities in South India so that we can design informed interventions to mitigate and manage this neglected tropical disease. There's much to be done.
